{
  "doc_id": "43727",
  "text": "Collagen cross-linking has been described as a major factor in fibrosis of multiple tissues, [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] including the heart. [CITATION_3] The role of collagen crosslinking in the heart is of great clinical significance in patients with DMD, as it also undergoes a fibrotic response. Whereas Lox mRNA is known to be increased in mdx cardiac muscle, [CITATION_4] LOX protein levels and collagen cross-linking have not been studied but should be a target of future investigation. Increased collagen cross-linking is thought to lead to a stiffer ECM and tissue, as demonstrated in the left ventricle of the fibrotic heart. [CITATION_5] However, recent reports of muscle stiffness in mdx mice have shown relatively more stiffening of limb muscle as opposed to the diaphragm, [CITATION_6] even though cross-linking is most prevalent in the diaphragm. Collagen content shows little correlation with passive stiffness, [CITATION_7] but collagen cross-linking does not account for additional variability in muscle fiber bundle stiffness. [CITATION_8] This suggests that, although collagen may be stiffer at the molecular level, other parameters of collagen organization dictate muscle stiffness at the tissue level. However, this does not preclude the micro-stiffness of the cross-linked collagen fibrils from playing a critical role in the cellular response to collagen crosslinking in fibrosis. LOX is critical to the integrity of the developing diaphragm, as mice that lack LOX often die perinatally from diaphragmatic hernias. [CITATION_9] Further, skeletal muscle development is disrupted in LOX knockout mice independent of skeletal or tendon defects, demonstrating a role for LOX in this process.",
